pr_review_body:
@AlirezaH320 thanks for being so speedy on this! I wasn't expecting you to move so fast, haha :smile:.

This is a great PR and I appreciate the work that went in. Thanks for handling this matter. In fact, I can see how this idea of a _reference data_ for colormaps could be really handy. Your PR lays the groundwork for exploring more semantics here, and I'm seeing some cool possibilities.

Meanwhile, just some small requested changes. Where it was simple enough for me to do, I directly suggested changes to speed things up for you.

Lots of changes. So, this is a major refactoring job addressing 2 issues; #974 and ?.
Probably it would be a good idea to change the title;
`Add {set,get}_bucket_versioning() APIs`

Really clean and well formatted code :clap: 

@salexan2001 I think `black` found a few issues, and caused the CI build to fail. Could you try running `make format` locally to update the code and update the PR, please?

That should fix the build. Thanks!

Thanks for the PR. I wrote a few tests for this that seem to hang forever. I added more combinations of tasks and actors interchanging references and values. It seems the failures happen when you get the objects in a different order of their remote call or if you do not call `Ray::Get` on an object before it is used by the next remote call e.g., (the code after the comment `/// actor task with args which pass by reference`). I was not able to add commits to this PR because I do not seem to have access to this repo, but here is the `cluster_mode_test.cc` that I am using, can we actually replace the current `cluster_mode_test.cc` with this? The test hangs forever, can you please take a look? Our goal here for this to be merged is to get the new test to pass. Can we please do that?

```

#include <gtest/gtest.h>
#include <ray/api.h>
#include <ray/api/ray_config.h>
#include <ray/experimental/default_worker.h>

using namespace ::ray::api;

/// general function of user code
int Return1() { return 1; }
int Plus1(int x) { return x + 1; }
int Plus(int x, int y) { return x + y; }

/// a class of user code
class Counter {
 public:
  int count;

  Counter(int init) { count = init; }
  static Counter *FactoryCreate() { return new Counter(0); }
  static Counter *FactoryCreate(int init) { return new Counter(init); }
  static Counter *FactoryCreate(int init1, int init2) { return new Counter(init1+init2); }
  /// non static function
  int Plus1() {
    count += 1;
    return count;
  }
  int Add(int x) {
    count += x;
    return count;
  }
};

TEST(RayClusterModeTest, FullTest) {
  /// initialization to cluster mode
  ray::api::RayConfig::GetInstance()->run_mode = RunMode::CLUSTER;
  /// TODO(Guyang Song): add the dynamic library name
  ray::api::RayConfig::GetInstance()->lib_name = "";
  Ray::Init();

  /// put and get object
  auto obj = Ray::Put(12345);
  auto get_result = *(Ray::Get(obj));
  EXPECT_EQ(12345, get_result);

  /// common task without args
  auto task_obj = Ray::Task(Return1).Remote();
  int task_result = *(Ray::Get(task_obj));
  EXPECT_EQ(1, task_result);

  /// common task with args
  task_obj = Ray::Task(Plus1, 5).Remote();
  task_result = *(Ray::Get(task_obj));
  EXPECT_EQ(6, task_result);

  /// actor task without args
  ActorHandle<Counter> actor1 = Ray::Actor(Counter::FactoryCreate).Remote();
  auto actor_object1 = actor1.Task(&Counter::Plus1).Remote();
  int actor_task_result1 = *(Ray::Get(actor_object1));
  EXPECT_EQ(1, actor_task_result1);

  /// actor task with args
  ActorHandle<Counter> actor2 = Ray::Actor(Counter::FactoryCreate, 1).Remote();
  auto actor_object2 = actor2.Task(&Counter::Add, 5).Remote();

  /// actor task with args which pass by reference
  ActorHandle<Counter> actor3 = Ray::Actor(Counter::FactoryCreate, 6).Remote();
  auto actor_object3 = actor3.Task(&Counter::Add, actor_object2).Remote();
  int actor_task_result3 = *(Ray::Get(actor_object3));
  EXPECT_EQ(12, actor_task_result3);
  
  int actor_task_result2 = *(Ray::Get(actor_object2));
  EXPECT_EQ(6, actor_task_result2);
 
  /// general function remote call（args passed by value）
  auto r0 = Ray::Task(Return1).Remote();
  auto r1 = Ray::Task(Plus1, 30).Remote();
  auto r2 = Ray::Task(Plus, 3, 22).Remote();

  int result1 = *(Ray::Get(r1));
  int result0 = *(Ray::Get(r0));
  int result2 = *(Ray::Get(r2));
  EXPECT_EQ(result0, 1);
  EXPECT_EQ(result1, 31); 
  EXPECT_EQ(result2, 25);

  /// general function remote call（args passed by reference）
  auto r3 = Ray::Task(Return1).Remote();
  auto r4 = Ray::Task(Plus1, r3).Remote();
  auto r5 = Ray::Task(Plus, r4, r3).Remote();
  auto r6 = Ray::Task(Plus, r4, 10).Remote();

  int result5 = *(Ray::Get(r5));
  int result4 = *(Ray::Get(r4));
  int result6 = *(Ray::Get(r6));
  //int result3 = *(Ray::Get(r3));
  EXPECT_EQ(result0, 1);
  EXPECT_EQ(result4, 2);
  EXPECT_EQ(result5, 3);
  EXPECT_EQ(result6, 12); 
 
  /// create actor and actor function remote call with args passed by value
  ActorHandle<Counter> actor4 = Ray::Actor(Counter::FactoryCreate, 10).Remote();
  auto r7 = actor4.Task(&Counter::Add, 5).Remote();
  auto r8 = actor4.Task(&Counter::Add, 1).Remote();
  auto r9 = actor4.Task(&Counter::Add, 3).Remote();
  auto r10 = actor4.Task(&Counter::Add, 8).Remote();

  int result7 = *(Ray::Get(r7));
  int result8 = *(Ray::Get(r8));
  int result9 = *(Ray::Get(r9));
  int result10 = *(Ray::Get(r10));
  EXPECT_EQ(result7, 15);
  EXPECT_EQ(result8, 16);
  EXPECT_EQ(result9, 19);
  EXPECT_EQ(result10, 27); 

  /// create actor and task function remote call with args passed by reference
  ActorHandle<Counter> actor5 = Ray::Actor(Counter::FactoryCreate, r10).Remote();
  auto r11 = actor5.Task(&Counter::Add, r0).Remote();
  auto r12 = actor5.Task(&Counter::Add, r11).Remote();
  auto r13 = actor5.Task(&Counter::Add, r10).Remote();
  auto r14 = actor5.Task(&Counter::Add, r13).Remote();
  auto r15 = Ray::Task(Plus, r0, r11).Remote();
  auto r16 = Ray::Task(Plus1, r15).Remote();

  int result12 = *(Ray::Get(r12));
  int result14 = *(Ray::Get(r14));
  int result11 = *(Ray::Get(r11));
  int result13 = *(Ray::Get(r13));
  int result16 = *(Ray::Get(r16));
  int result15 = *(Ray::Get(r15));
  
  EXPECT_EQ(result11, 28);
  EXPECT_EQ(result12, 56);
  EXPECT_EQ(result13, 83);
  EXPECT_EQ(result14, 166); 
  EXPECT_EQ(result15, 29); 
  EXPECT_EQ(result16, 30); 
 
  Ray::Shutdown();
}

/// TODO(Guyang Song): Separate default worker from this test.
/// Currently, we compile `default_worker` and `cluster_mode_test` in one single binary,
/// to work around a symbol conflicting issue.
/// This is the main function of the binary, and we use the `is_default_worker` arg to
/// tell if this binary is used as `default_worker` or `cluster_mode_test`.
int main(int argc, char **argv) {
  const char *default_worker_magic = "is_default_worker";
  /// `is_default_worker` is the last arg of `argv`
  if (argc > 1 &&
      memcmp(argv[argc - 1], default_worker_magic, strlen(default_worker_magic)) == 0) {
    default_worker_main(argc, argv);
    return 0;
  }
  ::testing::InitGoogleTest(&argc, argv);
  return RUN_ALL_TESTS();
}

```

@rtibbles 

Ignore the above - after `make clean`-ing my pyc files I cannot replicate this despite my best efforts. Always the server.pid file is killed between runs.

Oh - but don't ignore the bit about the docstring if you wouldn't mind quickly updating that before merging.

I do think the use of `hostname` and `port` here can be confusing to cover both `http` and `unix` URIs. Stepping back a bit, I think a minimal change that gets the behavior I understand you are going for could be to leave the constants as is but add:

```
DEFAULT_TRACE_UNIX_PATH = "/var/run/datadog/apm.socket"
DEFAULT_STATS_UNIX_PATH = "/var/run/datadog/dsd.socket"
```

Then modify the url functions to check them:

```
def get_trace_url():
    # type: () -> str
    if os.path.exists(DEFAULT_TRACE_UNIX_PATH):
        return "unix://{}".format(DEFAULT_TRACE_UNIX_PATH) 

    url = os.environ.get("DD_TRACE_AGENT_URL", "http://%s:%d" % (get_hostname(), get_trace_port()))
    return url


def get_stats_url():
    # type: () -> str
    if os.path.exists(DEFAULT_STATS_UNIX_PATH):
        return "unix://{}".format(DEFAULT_STATS_UNIX_PATH) 

    return get_env(
        "dogstatsd", "url", default="udp://{}:{}".format(get_hostname(), get_stats_port())
    )  # type: ignore[return-value]
```

What do you think?

I think you have 2 bugs that cancelled out in test cases here. I think some test like 

```
@ray.remote
def f():
 sleep(10000)

@ray.remote
def g():
 ray.get(h.remote())

@ray.remote
def h():
 sleep(10000)

ray.get([f.remote() for _ in range(10000)].extend([g.remote() for _ in range(1000)]))
```

will fail (note that the nested task is just one way of causing 2 tasks to have the same resource shape but separate scheduling classes. (it may not hurt to also have a test case with 2 tasks of the same resource shape but different scheduling classes, but i leave that up to you).

@LongnoseRob, changes are ok for me.
Thanks a lot for your contribution.
There's a small detail that popped up recently in another PR. Could you please rename `resourceName` to `adapter` in the code ?

The tests and all the core logic makes sense. There are a few cases that I think might've been missed.

As @RobbieMcKinstry pointed out, the PropertyPath.reset implementation is a bit difficult to follow.
The comments help, but I'm wondering about how we can make this more maintainable.
I think one easy bit might be to branch on "leaf or not" first, and then on types, since the bulk of the code is in the leaf handling.

```go
if len(p) > 1 {
  // Not a leaf. Traverse.
  key, p := p[0], p[1:]
  switch key := key.(type) {
  // ...
  }
}

// Leaf. Reset matched values.
switch key := key.(type) {
// ...
}
```

@sryza @prha, I did a very rough pass at making a context specific for multi asset sensors that would allow users to fetch events in the sensor body more easily. Not sure it fully works yet, but I want to get some initial feedback on the user facing API to decide if this makes sense as the way to go. If we do go this direction, i'll update the rest of the code and clean it up. 

the sensors in `toys/asset_sensors.py` have been updated to use the new version so that's a good file to look at

i left a couple comments in the PR on specific places where I have questions/thoughts
